{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775861326438,"sessionID":"ses_2866ae9a5ffeJaOf2Df4gOXgas","part":{"id":"prt_d799558bf001WGUt6q3KGzaSxT","messageID":"msg_d79954c40001paCR5nN5B4du3f","sessionID":"ses_2866ae9a5ffeJaOf2Df4gOXgas","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_573aa7278990428282c28896","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-015-proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-015-proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-015: PicoD Command Execution API\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: \n5: This proposal implements the PicoD command execution API for the `pkg/picod` module in the AgentCube project. The goal is to:\n6: \n7: 1. **Secure Command Execution** - Execute commands within controlled sandbox environments with proper isolation\n8: 2. **Resource Limit Enforcement** - Enforce CPU, memory, time, and output size limits on command execution\n9: 3. **Output Capture and Streaming** - Capture stdout/stderr with optional streaming for long-running commands\n10: 4. **Cancellation Support** - Enable command cancellation via context for graceful termination\n11: 5. **Security Hardening** - Implement security validations to prevent privilege escalation and command injection\n12: \n13: This implementation builds upon the sandbox infrastructure established in AR-012 and provides the execution engine for code interpreters and agent runtimes.\n14: \n15: ## Scope\n16: \n17: **Module:** `pkg/picod`  \n18: **Language:** Go  \n19: **Size:** M\n20: \n21: This AR covers:\n22: \n23: - **In scope:**\n24:   - Core `PicoD` struct and initialization (`picod.go`)\n25:   - Command execution logic with resource limits (`executor.go`)\n26:   - Resource limit configuration and enforcement (`limits.go`)\n27:   - Output capture and streaming (`output.go`)\n28:   - Security validations and sandboxing (`security.go`)\n29:   - Unit tests with mocked executors\n30:   - Integration tests with real command execution\n31:   - Configuration via environment variables\n32: \n33: - **Out of scope:**\n34:   - Container runtime integration (covered in AR-005, AR-009)\n35:   - Network namespace manipulation\n36:   - User namespace management\n37:   - Filesystem isolation beyond chroot/workspace jail\n38:   - Distributed command execution\n39:   - PicoD HTTP daemon (covered in `code-execution/` specs)\n40: \n41: ## Current State Analysis\n42: \n43: ### Existing Sandbox Infrastructure\n44: \n45: The current system has sandbox management infrastructure:\n46: \n47: 1. **Sandbox Manager** (`pkg/workloadmanager/sandbox/`):\n48:    - Creates and manages sandbox pods\n49:    - Handles lifecycle (create, update, delete)\n50:    - Supports warm pool for pre-provisioned sandboxes\n51: \n52: 2. **CodeInterpreter CRD** (`pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1/types.go`):\n53:    - Defines `CodeInterpreterSpec` with image, command, args, env, resources\n54:    - Supports `AuthMode` enum (`picod` or `none`)\n55:    - Default image: `volcanosh/picod:latest`\n56: \n57: 3. **Workload Manager**:\n58:    - Handles `CodeInterpreter` resources\n59:    - Creates underlying sandbox pods\n60:    - Injects `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` when `AuthMode=picod`\n61: \n62: ### Gaps Identified\n63: \n64: 1. **No unified execution API** - Command execution logic is scattered or non-existent\n65: 2. **No resource limit enforcement** - No programmatic way to enforce CPU/memory/time limits\n66: 3. **No output streaming** - Cannot stream output for long-running commands\n67: 4. **No security hardening** - Missing input validation and sandboxing at the API level\n68: 5. **No cancellation support** - Cannot gracefully cancel running commands\n69: \n70: ### PicoD Context\n71: \n72: Per `code-execution/design.md` and `code-execution/spec.md`:\n73: - PicoD is an HTTP daemon that runs commands inside a configurable workspace jail\n74: - Exposes health endpoint with JWT (RSA)-protected APIs\n75: - CLI flags: `-port` (default 8080), `-workspace` (default: current working directory)\n76: - Server uses `ReadHeaderTimeout` of 10 seconds\n77: \n78: ## Proposed Changes\n79: \n80: ### 1. Core PicoD Structure (`picod.go`)\n81: \n82: ```go\n83: // PicoD represents a command execution sandbox\n84: type PicoD struct {\n85:     sandboxID    string\n86:     workDir      string\n87:     limits       *ResourceLimits\n88:     securityOpts *SecurityOptions\n89:     logger       klog.Logger\n90: }\n91: \n92: // Option is a functional option for PicoD\n93: type Option func(*PicoD)\n94: \n95: // New creates a new PicoD instance\n96: func New(sandboxID string, opts ...Option) *PicoD\n97: \n98: // WithWorkDir sets the working directory\n99: func WithWorkDir(dir string) Option\n100: \n101: // WithLimits sets resource limits\n102: func WithLimits(limits *ResourceLimits) Option\n103: \n104: // WithSecurityOpts sets security options\n105: func WithSecurityOpts(opts *SecurityOptions) Option\n106: \n107: // WithLogger sets the logger\n108: func WithLogger(logger klog.Logger) Option\n109: ```\n110: \n111: ### 2. Resource Limits (`limits.go`)\n112: \n113: ```go\n114: // ResourceLimits defines execution resource limits\n115: type ResourceLimits struct {\n116:     // Timeout is the maximum execution duration\n117:     Timeout time.Duration\n118:     \n119:     // MaxCPU is the maximum CPU cores (e.g., 0.5, 1.0)\n120:     MaxCPU float64\n121:     \n122:     // MaxMemory is the maximum memory in bytes\n123:     MaxMemory int64\n124:     \n125:     // MaxOutputSize is the maximum output size in bytes\n126:     MaxOutputSize int64\n127:     \n128:     // MaxProcesses is the maximum number of processes\n129:     MaxProcesses int\n130: }\n131: \n132: // DefaultResourceLimits returns default resource limits\n133: func DefaultResourceLimits() *ResourceLimits\n134: \n135: // Validate validates resource limits\n136: func (l *ResourceLimits) Validate() error\n137: ```\n138: \n139: ### 3. Security Options (`security.go`)\n140: \n141: ```go\n142: // SecurityOptions defines security settings for command execution\n143: type SecurityOptions struct {\n144:     // UID is the user ID to run commands as\n145:     UID int\n146:     \n147:     // GID is the group ID to run commands as\n148:     GID int\n149:     \n150:     // Capabilities is the list of allowed capabilities\n151:     Capabilities []string\n152:     \n153:     // ReadOnlyFS makes the filesystem read-only\n154:     ReadOnlyFS bool\n155:     \n156:     // NoNetwork disables network access\n157:     NoNetwork bool\n158:     \n159:     // AllowedCommands is an optional allowlist of command paths\n160:     AllowedCommands []string\n161: }\n162: \n163: // DefaultSecurityOpts returns default security options\n164: func DefaultSecurityOpts() *SecurityOptions\n165: \n166: // Validate validates security options\n167: func (o *SecurityOptions) Validate() error\n168: ```\n169: \n170: ### 4. Command Execution API (`executor.go`)\n171: \n172: ```go\n173: // Command represents a command to execute\n174: type Command struct {\n175:     // Path is the command path\n176:     Path string\n177:     \n178:     // Args are the command arguments\n179:     Args []string\n180:     \n181:     // Env is the environment variables\n182:     Env []string\n183:     \n184:     // Dir is the working directory\n185:     Dir string\n186:     \n187:     // Stdin is the standard input\n188:     Stdin io.Reader\n189:     \n190:     // Stdout is the standard output (optional, captured if nil)\n191:     Stdout io.Writer\n192:     \n193:     // Stderr is the standard error (optional, captured if nil)\n194:     Stderr io.Writer\n195: }\n196: \n197: // CommandResult represents the result of command execution\n198: type CommandResult struct {\n199:     // ExitCode is the process exit code\n200:     ExitCode int\n201:     \n202:     // Stdout is the captured standard output\n203:     Stdout []byte\n204:     \n205:     // Stderr is the captured standard error\n206:     Stderr []byte\n207:     \n208:     // Duration is the execution duration\n209:     Duration time.Duration\n210:     \n211:     // OOMKilled indicates if the process was killed due to OOM\n212:     OOMKilled bool\n213:     \n214:     // Timeout indicates if the command timed out\n215:     Timeout bool\n216: }\n217: \n218: // Run executes a command and waits for completion\n219: func (p *PicoD) Run(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command) (*CommandResult, error)\n220: \n221: // Start starts a command without waiting\n222: func (p *PicoD) Start(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command) (*Process, error)\n223: \n224: // Process represents a running process\n225: type Process struct {\n226:     // PID is the process ID\n227:     PID int\n228:     \n229:     // Wait waits for the process to complete\n230:     Wait() (*CommandResult, error)\n231:     \n232:     // Kill sends a signal to the process\n233:     Kill(signal os.Signal) error\n234: }\n235: ```\n236: \n237: ### 5. Output Streaming (`output.go`)\n238: \n239: ```go\n240: // OutputHandler handles streaming output\n241: type OutputHandler interface {\n242:     // OnStdout is called when stdout data is available\n243:     OnStdout(data []byte)\n244:     \n245:     // OnStderr is called when stderr data is available\n246:     OnStderr(data []byte)\n247:     \n248:     // OnComplete is called when execution completes\n249:     OnComplete(result *CommandResult)\n250: }\n251: \n252: // RunWithStreaming executes a command with streaming output\n253: func (p *PicoD) RunWithStreaming(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command, handler OutputHandler) (*CommandResult, error)\n254: ```\n255: \n256: ### 6. Security Validation (`security.go`)\n257: \n258: ```go\n259: // ValidateCommand validates a command for security\n260: func ValidateCommand(cmd *Command, opts *SecurityOptions) error\n261: \n262: // IsPathSafe checks if a path is within the allowed workspace\n263: func IsPathSafe(path, workDir string) bool\n264: \n265: // DropPrivileges drops privileges to the specified UID/GID\n266: func DropPrivileges(uid, gid int) error\n267: \n268: // SetResourceLimits applies resource limits to the current process\n269: func SetResourceLimits(limits *ResourceLimits) error\n270: ```\n271: \n272: ### 7. Configuration\n273: \n274: #### Environment Variables\n275: \n276: | Variable | Required | Default | Notes |\n277: |----------|----------|---------|-------|\n278: | `PICOD_WORKDIR` | No | `/tmp/picod` | Base working directory |\n279: | `PICOD_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT` | No | `30s` | Default command timeout |\n280: | `PICOD_MAX_MEMORY` | No | `128Mi` | Default memory limit |\n281: | `PICOD_MAX_CPU` | No | `1.0` | Default CPU limit |\n282: | `PICOD_MAX_OUTPUT_SIZE` | No | `10MB` | Default output size limit |\n283: | `PICOD_MAX_PROCESSES` | No | `10` | Default process limit |\n284: \n285: ### 8. Error Handling\n286: \n287: ```go\n288: // ExecutionError represents an execution error\n289: type ExecutionError struct {\n290:     // Type is the error type\n291:     Type ExecutionErrorType\n292:     \n293:     // Message is the error message\n294:     Message string\n295:     \n296:     // Underlying is the underlying error\n297:     Underlying error\n298: }\n299: \n300: type ExecutionErrorType string\n301: \n302: const (\n303:     ExecutionErrorTimeout    ExecutionErrorType = \"timeout\"\n304:     ExecutionErrorOOM        ExecutionErrorType = \"oom\"\n305:     ExecutionErrorCancelled  ExecutionErrorType = \"cancelled\"\n306:     ExecutionErrorSecurity   ExecutionErrorType = \"security\"\n307:     ExecutionErrorResource   ExecutionErrorType = \"resource\"\n308:     ExecutionErrorExec       ExecutionErrorType = \"exec\"\n309: )\n310: ```\n311: \n312: ## Impact Analysis\n313: \n314: ### Dependencies\n315: \n316: | Package | Purpose |\n317: |---------|---------|\n318: | `context` | Command cancellation and timeouts |\n319: | `os/exec` | Command execution primitives |\n320: | `syscall` | Process management and signals |\n321: | `k8s.io/klog/v2` | Structured logging |\n322: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/common/types` | SandboxInfo type definitions |\n323: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1` | Type definitions |\n324: \n325: ### Affected Components\n326: \n327: 1. **Sandbox Manager** (`pkg/workloadmanager/sandbox/`): Will use PicoD for command execution within sandboxes\n328: 2. **Workload Manager** (`pkg/workloadmanager/`): Will invoke PicoD APIs for job execution\n329: 3. **Code Interpreter** (standalone daemon): Will use PicoD execution logic\n330: 4. **Security Module**: Will configure security policies for command execution\n331: 5. **Monitoring System**: Will collect metrics from command execution\n332: \n333: ### Backward Compatibility\n334: \n335: - This is a new module with no existing API surface\n336: - No breaking changes to existing components\n337: - Configuration via environment variables and programmatic API\n338: - Existing `CodeInterpreter` CRD already references PicoD image\n339: \n340: ### Risk Assessment\n341: \n342: | Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n343: |------|------------|--------|------------|\n344: | Command injection | Low | High | Input validation, allowlist-based command selection |\n345: | Resource exhaustion | Medium | High | Enforce strict CPU/memory/time limits |\n346: | Privilege escalation | Low | Critical | Run as non-root, drop capabilities, use namespaces |\n347: | Output buffer overflow | Low | Medium | Stream large outputs, enforce size limits |\n348: | Zombie processes | Medium | Low | Proper process reaping, signal handling |\n349: \n350: ## Alternatives Considered\n351: \n352: ### Alternative 1: Use Existing Library (e.g., go-execute, bazel-remote)\n353: \n354: **Approach**: Leverage existing command execution libraries\n355: \n356: **Pros**:\n357: - Less code to maintain\n358: - Battle-tested implementations\n359: - Community support\n360: \n361: **Cons**:\n362: - May not meet specific security requirements for sandboxed execution\n363: - Additional dependency management overhead\n364: - Less control over resource limit enforcement\n365: - May not support Kubernetes-native patterns\n366: \n367: **Decision**: Implement custom solution for full control over security and limits, and better integration with AgentCube architecture.\n368: \n369: ### Alternative 2: Shell-based Execution\n370: \n371: **Approach**: Execute commands via `/bin/sh -c`\n372: \n373: **Pros**:\n374: - Simple implementation\n375: - Shell features (pipes, redirection) available\n376: - Familiar syntax\n377: \n378: **Cons**:\n379: - Security risks (shell injection attacks)\n380: - Harder to control resource limits accurately\n381: - Additional attack surface\n382: - Non-deterministic behavior across shells\n383: \n384: **Decision**: Use direct execve-style execution for better security and control.\n385: \n386: ### Alternative 3: Container-based Execution\n387: \n388: **Approach**: Spawn a new container for each command\n389: \n390: **Pros**:\n391: - Strong isolation\n392: - Built-in resource limits via cgroups\n393: - Clean environment per command\n394: \n395: **Cons**:\n396: - High overhead (container startup latency)\n397: - Requires container runtime access\n398: - Complex orchestration\n399: - Overkill for simple command execution\n400: \n401: **Decision**: Use process-level isolation with proper limits for lower latency; container isolation is handled at the sandbox pod level (AR-005).\n402: \n403: ## Testing Strategy\n404: \n405: ### Unit Tests\n406: \n407: 1. **TestPicoD_Run_Success**: Basic command execution\n408: 2. **TestPicoD_Run_Timeout**: Command exceeds timeout\n409: 3. **TestPicoD_Run_OOM**: Command exceeds memory limit\n410: 4. **TestPicoD_Run_Cancelled**: Context cancellation\n411: 5. **TestPicoD_OutputCapture**: Stdout/stderr capture\n412: 6. **TestPicoD_SecurityValidation**: Invalid commands rejected\n413: 7. **TestPicoD_ResourceLimits_Validate**: Resource limit validation\n414: 8. **TestPicoD_SecurityOpts_Validate**: Security options validation\n415: 9. **TestPicoD_WithOptions**: Functional options pattern\n416: 10. **TestPicoD_ExecutionErrorTypes**: Error type classification\n417: \n418: ### Integration Tests\n419: \n420: 1. **TestPicoD_Integration_FullLifecycle**: Full execution flow\n421: 2. **TestPicoD_Integration_Concurrent**: Multiple concurrent commands\n422: 3. **TestPicoD_Integration_ResourceLimits**: Verify limits are enforced\n423: 4. **TestPicoD_Integration_Streaming**: Output streaming functionality\n424: 5. **TestPicoD_Integration_SignalHandling**: Process signal handling\n425: \n426: ## Acceptance Criteria\n427: \n428: - [ ] `PicoD` struct implements all required methods\n429: - [ ] Resource limits are enforced (timeout, CPU, memory, output size)\n430: - [ ] Output capture works correctly (stdout, stderr, exit code)\n431: - [ ] Cancellation via context is supported\n432: - [ ] Security validations prevent dangerous operations\n433: - [ ] Streaming output is supported\n434: - [ ] All unit tests pass\n435: - [ ] Integration tests pass\n436: - [ ] Code coverage >= 80%\n437: - [ ] Documentation includes usage examples\n438: - [ ] Error types are properly classified and documented\n439: \n440: ## References\n441: \n442: - Sandbox Infrastructure: `changes/AR-012/proposal.md`\n443: - Session Storage: `changes/AR-013/proposal.md`\n444: - Valkey Storage: `changes/AR-014/proposal.md`\n445: - PicoD Spec: `code-execution/spec.md`\n446: - PicoD Design: `code-execution/design.md`\n447: - Client-Go: `deployment/client-go.md`\n\n(End of file - total 447 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-015: PicoD Command Execution API\n\n## Purpose\n\nThis proposal implements the PicoD command execution API for the `pkg/picod` module in the AgentCube project. The goal is to:\n\n1. **Secure Command Execution** - Execute commands within controlled sandbox environments with proper isolation\n2. **Resource Limit Enforcement** - Enforce CPU, memory, time, and output size limits on command execution\n3. **Output Capture and Streaming** - Capture stdout/stderr with optional streaming for long-running commands\n4. **Cancellation Support** - Enable command cancellation via context for graceful termination\n5. **Security Hardening** - Implement security validations to prevent privilege escalation and command injection\n\nThis implementation builds upon the sandbox infrastructure established in AR-012 and provides the execution engine for code interpreters and agent runtimes.\n\n## Scope\n\n**Module:** `pkg/picod`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-015-proposal.md","time":{"start":1775861326423,"end":1775861326436}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775861326451,"sessionID":"ses_2866ae9a5ffeJaOf2Df4gOXgas","part":{"id":"prt_d79955dcc001XbyGO62Dif10r2","messageID":"msg_d79954c40001paCR5nN5B4du3f","sessionID":"ses_2866ae9a5ffeJaOf2Df4gOXgas","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_5b80f9fb95dd40419256e8af","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/pkg/picod/design.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/pkg/picod/design.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Design: AR-015 PicoD Command Execution API\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: | Item | Value |\n6: |------|-------|\n7: | AR | AR-015 — PicoD Command Execution API |\n8: | Module | `pkg/picod` |\n9: | Language | Go |\n10: | Size | M |\n11: | Stage | ST-1 completed |\n12: \n13: This document describes the technical implementation for the PicoD command execution API within `pkg/picod`. The PicoD module provides secure, resource-limited command execution capabilities for the AgentCube platform, serving as the execution engine for code interpreters and agent runtimes.\n14: \n15: ## Architecture\n16: \n17: ### Component Structure\n18: \n19: ```\n20: pkg/picod/\n21: ├── picod.go                 # Main PicoD struct and initialization\n22: ├── picod_test.go            # PicoD unit tests\n23: ├── executor.go              # Command execution logic\n24: ├── executor_test.go         # Execution unit tests\n25: ├── limits.go                # Resource limit definitions and enforcement\n26: ├── limits_test.go           # Resource limit tests\n27: ├── security.go              # Security validation and hardening\n28: ├── security_test.go         # Security tests\n29: ├── output.go                # Output capture and streaming\n30: ├── output_test.go           # Output handling tests\n31: ├── process.go               # Running process management\n32: ├── process_test.go          # Process management tests\n33: ├── errors.go                # Error type definitions\n34: └── config.go                # Configuration from environment\n35: ```\n36: \n37: ### Integration Points\n38: \n39: - **os/exec**: Standard library command execution primitives\n40: - **syscall**: Process management, signals, and resource limits\n41: - **context**: Command cancellation and timeouts\n42: - **k8s.io/klog/v2**: Structured logging\n43: - **pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1**: Type definitions for CodeInterpreter\n44: - **pkg/common/types**: SandboxInfo type definitions\n45: \n46: ### Execution Flow\n47: \n48: ```\n49: Client (WorkloadManager/CodeInterpreter)\n50:   ↓\n51: PicoD.New(sandboxID, options...)\n52:   ↓\n53: PicoD.Run(ctx, Command)\n54:   ├─ ValidateCommand(cmd, securityOpts)\n55:   ├─ ApplyResourceLimits(limits)\n56:   ├─ exec.CommandContext(ctx, path, args...)\n57:   ├─ Configure cmd.SysProcAttr\n58:   ├─ Start process\n59:   ├─ Monitor with timeout/limits\n60:   ├─ Capture stdout/stderr\n61:   └─ Return CommandResult\n62: ```\n63: \n64: ## Data Structures\n65: \n66: ### PicoD\n67: \n68: ```go\n69: // PicoD represents a command execution sandbox\n70: type PicoD struct {\n71:     sandboxID    string\n72:     workDir      string\n73:     limits       *ResourceLimits\n74:     securityOpts *SecurityOptions\n75:     logger       klog.Logger\n76: }\n77: \n78: // Option is a functional option for PicoD\n79: type Option func(*PicoD)\n80: ```\n81: \n82: ### ResourceLimits\n83: \n84: ```go\n85: // ResourceLimits defines execution resource limits\n86: type ResourceLimits struct {\n87:     // Timeout is the maximum execution duration\n88:     Timeout time.Duration\n89:     \n90:     // MaxCPU is the maximum CPU cores (e.g., 0.5, 1.0)\n91:     MaxCPU float64\n92:     \n93:     // MaxMemory is the maximum memory in bytes\n94:     MaxMemory int64\n95:     \n96:     // MaxOutputSize is the maximum output size in bytes\n97:     MaxOutputSize int64\n98:     \n99:     // MaxProcesses is the maximum number of processes\n100:     MaxProcesses int\n101: }\n102: ```\n103: \n104: ### SecurityOptions\n105: \n106: ```go\n107: // SecurityOptions defines security settings for command execution\n108: type SecurityOptions struct {\n109:     // UID is the user ID to run commands as\n110:     UID int\n111:     \n112:     // GID is the group ID to run commands as\n113:     GID int\n114:     \n115:     // Capabilities is the list of allowed capabilities\n116:     Capabilities []string\n117:     \n118:     // ReadOnlyFS makes the filesystem read-only\n119:     ReadOnlyFS bool\n120:     \n121:     // NoNetwork disables network access\n122:     NoNetwork bool\n123:     \n124:     // AllowedCommands is an optional allowlist of command paths\n125:     AllowedCommands []string\n126: }\n127: ```\n128: \n129: ### Command\n130: \n131: ```go\n132: // Command represents a command to execute\n133: type Command struct {\n134:     // Path is the command path\n135:     Path string\n136:     \n137:     // Args are the command arguments\n138:     Args []string\n139:     \n140:     // Env is the environment variables\n141:     Env []string\n142:     \n143:     // Dir is the working directory\n144:     Dir string\n145:     \n146:     // Stdin is the standard input\n147:     Stdin io.Reader\n148:     \n149:     // Stdout is the standard output (optional, captured if nil)\n150:     Stdout io.Writer\n151:     \n152:     // Stderr is the standard error (optional, captured if nil)\n153:     Stderr io.Writer\n154: }\n155: ```\n156: \n157: ### CommandResult\n158: \n159: ```go\n160: // CommandResult represents the result of command execution\n161: type CommandResult struct {\n162:     // ExitCode is the process exit code\n163:     ExitCode int\n164:     \n165:     // Stdout is the captured standard output\n166:     Stdout []byte\n167:     \n168:     // Stderr is the captured standard error\n169:     Stderr []byte\n170:     \n171:     // Duration is the execution duration\n172:     Duration time.Duration\n173:     \n174:     // OOMKilled indicates if the process was killed due to OOM\n175:     OOMKilled bool\n176:     \n177:     // Timeout indicates if the command timed out\n178:     Timeout bool\n179: }\n180: ```\n181: \n182: ### Process\n183: \n184: ```go\n185: // Process represents a running process\n186: type Process struct {\n187:     // PID is the process ID\n188:     PID int\n189:     \n190:     // cmd is the underlying exec.Cmd\n191:     cmd *exec.Cmd\n192:     \n193:     // startTime is when the process started\n194:     startTime time.Time\n195: }\n196: ```\n197: \n198: ### OutputHandler\n199: \n200: ```go\n201: // OutputHandler handles streaming output\n202: type OutputHandler interface {\n203:     // OnStdout is called when stdout data is available\n204:     OnStdout(data []byte)\n205:     \n206:     // OnStderr is called when stderr data is available\n207:     OnStderr(data []byte)\n208:     \n209:     // OnComplete is called when execution completes\n210:     OnComplete(result *CommandResult)\n211: }\n212: ```\n213: \n214: ## API Contracts\n215: \n216: ### PicoD Initialization\n217: \n218: ```go\n219: // New creates a new PicoD instance\n220: func New(sandboxID string, opts ...Option) *PicoD\n221: \n222: // WithWorkDir sets the working directory\n223: func WithWorkDir(dir string) Option\n224: \n225: // WithLimits sets resource limits\n226: func WithLimits(limits *ResourceLimits) Option\n227: \n228: // WithSecurityOpts sets security options\n229: func WithSecurityOpts(opts *SecurityOptions) Option\n230: \n231: // WithLogger sets the logger\n232: func WithLogger(logger klog.Logger) Option\n233: ```\n234: \n235: ### Command Execution\n236: \n237: ```go\n238: // Run executes a command and waits for completion\n239: func (p *PicoD) Run(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command) (*CommandResult, error)\n240: \n241: // Start starts a command without waiting\n242: func (p *PicoD) Start(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command) (*Process, error)\n243: \n244: // RunWithStreaming executes a command with streaming output\n245: func (p *PicoD) RunWithStreaming(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command, handler OutputHandler) (*CommandResult, error)\n246: ```\n247: \n248: ### Process Management\n249: \n250: ```go\n251: // Wait waits for the process to complete\n252: func (p *Process) Wait() (*CommandResult, error)\n253: \n254: // Kill sends a signal to the process\n255: func (p *Process) Kill(signal os.Signal) error\n256: \n257: // Signal sends a specific signal to the process\n258: func (p *Process) Signal(sig syscall.Signal) error\n259: ```\n260: \n261: ### Resource Limits\n262: \n263: ```go\n264: // DefaultResourceLimits returns default resource limits\n265: func DefaultResourceLimits() *ResourceLimits\n266: \n267: // Validate validates resource limits\n268: func (l *ResourceLimits) Validate() error\n269: \n270: // Apply applies resource limits to a process\n271: func (l *ResourceLimits) Apply(cmd *exec.Cmd) error\n272: ```\n273: \n274: ### Security Validation\n275: \n276: ```go\n277: // DefaultSecurityOpts returns default security options\n278: func DefaultSecurityOpts() *SecurityOptions\n279: \n280: // Validate validates security options\n281: func (o *SecurityOptions) Validate() error\n282: \n283: // ValidateCommand validates a command for security\n284: func ValidateCommand(cmd *Command, opts *SecurityOptions) error\n285: \n286: // IsPathSafe checks if a path is within the allowed workspace\n287: func IsPathSafe(path, workDir string) bool\n288: ```\n289: \n290: ### Configuration\n291: \n292: ```go\n293: // LoadConfig loads configuration from environment variables\n294: func LoadConfig() (*Config, error)\n295: \n296: // Config holds PicoD configuration\n297: type Config struct {\n298:     WorkDir         string\n299:     DefaultTimeout  time.Duration\n300:     MaxMemory       int64\n301:     MaxCPU          float64\n302:     MaxOutputSize   int64\n303:     MaxProcesses    int\n304: }\n305: ```\n306: \n307: ## Error Handling\n308: \n309: ### ExecutionError\n310: \n311: ```go\n312: // ExecutionError represents an execution error\n313: type ExecutionError struct {\n314:     // Type is the error type\n315:     Type ExecutionErrorType\n316:     \n317:     // Message is the error message\n318:     Message string\n319:     \n320:     // Underlying is the underlying error\n321:     Underlying error\n322: }\n323: \n324: // Error implements the error interface\n325: func (e *ExecutionError) Error() string\n326: \n327: // Unwrap returns the underlying error\n328: func (e *ExecutionError) Unwrap() error\n329: ```\n330: \n331: ### ExecutionErrorType\n332: \n333: ```go\n334: type ExecutionErrorType string\n335: \n336: const (\n337:     ExecutionErrorTimeout    ExecutionErrorType = \"timeout\"\n338:     ExecutionErrorOOM        ExecutionErrorType = \"oom\"\n339:     ExecutionErrorCancelled  ExecutionErrorType = \"cancelled\"\n340:     ExecutionErrorSecurity   ExecutionErrorType = \"security\"\n341:     ExecutionErrorResource   ExecutionErrorType = \"resource\"\n342:     ExecutionErrorExec       ExecutionErrorType = \"exec\"\n343: )\n344: ```\n345: \n346: ### Error Conditions\n347: \n348: | Condition | Error Type | HTTP Mapping | Description |\n349: |-----------|------------|--------------|-------------|\n350: | Command exceeds timeout | `ExecutionErrorTimeout` | 408 Request Timeout | Command execution exceeded configured timeout |\n351: | Command exceeds memory | `ExecutionErrorOOM` | 413 Payload Too Large | Process was killed due to OOM |\n352: | Context cancelled | `ExecutionErrorCancelled` | 499 Client Closed Request | Client cancelled the operation |\n353: | Security violation | `ExecutionErrorSecurity` | 403 Forbidden | Command failed security validation |\n354: | Resource limit invalid | `ExecutionErrorResource` | 400 Bad Request | Invalid resource limit configuration |\n355: | Exec failure | `ExecutionErrorExec` | 500 Internal Server Error | Failed to start/execute command |\n356: \n357: ## Implementation Details\n358: \n359: ### PicoD Initialization\n360: \n361: ```go\n362: func New(sandboxID string, opts ...Option) *PicoD {\n363:     p := &PicoD{\n364:         sandboxID:    sandboxID,\n365:         workDir:      \"/tmp/picod/\" + sandboxID,\n366:         limits:       DefaultResourceLimits(),\n367:         securityOpts: DefaultSecurityOpts(),\n368:         logger:       klog.Background(),\n369:     }\n370:     \n371:     for _, opt := range opts {\n372:         opt(p)\n373:     }\n374:     \n375:     return p\n376: }\n377: ```\n378: \n379: ### Command Execution Flow\n380: \n381: ```go\n382: func (p *PicoD) Run(ctx context.Context, cmd *Command) (*CommandResult, error) {\n383:     // 1. Validate command\n384:     if err := ValidateCommand(cmd, p.securityOpts); err != nil {\n385:         return nil, &ExecutionError{\n386:             Type:    ExecutionErrorSecurity,\n387:             Message: \"command validation failed\",\n388:             Underlying: err,\n389:         }\n390:     }\n391:     \n392:     // 2. Create exec.Cmd\n393:     execCmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, cmd.Path, cmd.Args...)\n394:     \n395:     // 3. Configure environment\n396:     execCmd.Env = cmd.Env\n397:     execCmd.Dir = cmd.Dir\n398:     \n399:     // 4. Apply resource limits\n400:     if err := p.limits.Apply(execCmd); err != nil {\n401:         return nil, &ExecutionError{\n402:             Type:    ExecutionErrorResource,\n403:             Message: \"failed to apply resource limits\",\n404:             Underlying: err,\n405:         }\n406:     }\n407:     \n408:     // 5. Capture output\n409:     var stdoutBuf, stderrBuf bytes.Buffer\n410:     if cmd.Stdout == nil {\n411:         execCmd.Stdout = &stdoutBuf\n412:     } else {\n413:         execCmd.Stdout = cmd.Stdout\n414:     }\n415:     if cmd.Stderr == nil {\n416:         execCmd.Stderr = &stderrBuf\n417:     } else {\n418:         execCmd.Stderr = cmd.Stderr\n419:     }\n420:     \n421:     // 6. Start execution\n422:     startTime := time.Now()\n423:     if err := execCmd.Start(); err != nil {\n424:         return nil, &ExecutionError{\n425:             Type:    ExecutionErrorExec,\n426:             Message: \"failed to start command\",\n427:             Underlying: err,\n428:         }\n429:     }\n430:     \n431:     // 7. Wait for completion\n432:     err := execCmd.Wait()\n433:     duration := time.Since(startTime)\n434:     \n435:     // 8. Build result\n436:     result := &CommandResult{\n437:         Duration: duration,\n438:     }\n439:     \n440:     if cmd.Stdout == nil {\n441:         result.Stdout = stdoutBuf.Bytes()\n442:     }\n443:     if cmd.Stderr == nil {\n444:         result.Stderr = stderrBuf.Bytes()\n445:     }\n446:     \n447:     // 9. Check for timeout/OOM\n448:     if ctx.Err() == context.DeadlineExceeded {\n449:         result.Timeout = true\n450:         err = &ExecutionError{\n451:             Type:    ExecutionErrorTimeout,\n452:             Message: \"command timed out\",\n453:         }\n454:     }\n455:     \n456:     if exitErr, ok := err.(*exec.ExitError); ok {\n457:         if status, ok := exitErr.Sys().(syscall.WaitStatus); ok {\n458:             if status.Signal() == syscall.SIGKILL {\n459:                 result.OOMKilled = true\n460:                 err = &ExecutionError{\n461:                     Type:    ExecutionErrorOOM,\n462:                     Message: \"process killed due to OOM\",\n463:                 }\n464:             }\n465:         }\n466:         result.ExitCode = exitErr.ExitCode()\n467:     } else if err == nil {\n468:         result.ExitCode = 0\n469:     }\n470:     \n471:     return result, err\n472: }\n473: ```\n474: \n475: ### Resource Limit Enforcement\n476: \n477: ```go\n478: func (l *ResourceLimits) Apply(cmd *exec.Cmd) error {\n479:     if cmd.SysProcAttr == nil {\n480:         cmd.SysProcAttr = &syscall.SysProcAttr{}\n481:     }\n482:     \n483:     // Set CPU limits via cgroups (Linux)\n484:     if l.MaxCPU > 0 {\n485:         // Use cpu.cfs_quota_us and cpu.cfs_period_us\n486:         // This requires cgroup setup\n487:     }\n488:     \n489:     // Set memory limits\n490:     if l.MaxMemory > 0 {\n491:         cmd.SysProcAttr.Setpgid = true\n492:         // Memory limits via setrlimit\n493:         syscall.Setrlimit(syscall.RLIMIT_AS, &syscall.Rlimit{\n494:             Cur: uint64(l.MaxMemory),\n495:             Max: uint64(l.MaxMemory),\n496:         })\n497:     }\n498:     \n499:     // Set process limits\n500:     if l.MaxProcesses > 0 {\n501:         syscall.Setrlimit(syscall.RLIMIT_NPROC, &syscall.Rlimit{\n502:             Cur: uint64(l.MaxProcesses),\n503:             Max: uint64(l.MaxProcesses),\n504:         })\n505:     }\n506:     \n507:     return nil\n508: }\n509: ```\n510: \n511: ### Security Validation\n512: \n513: ```go\n514: func ValidateCommand(cmd *Command, opts *SecurityOptions) error {\n515:     // 1. Check if command path is in allowlist\n516:     if len(opts.AllowedCommands) > 0 {\n517:         allowed := false\n518:         for _, allowedCmd := range opts.AllowedCommands {\n519:             if cmd.Path == allowedCmd {\n520:                 allowed = true\n521:                 break\n522:             }\n523:         }\n524:         if !allowed {\n525:             return fmt.Errorf(\"command %q not in allowlist\", cmd.Path)\n526:         }\n527:     }\n528:     \n529:     // 2. Validate working directory\n530:     if cmd.Dir != \"\" && !IsPathSafe(cmd.Dir, opts.WorkDir) {\n531:         return fmt.Errorf(\"working directory %q is outside workspace\", cmd.Dir)\n532:     }\n533:     \n534:     // 3. Check for path traversal in arguments\n535:     for _, arg := range cmd.Args {\n536:         if strings.Contains(arg, \"..\") {\n537:             return fmt.Errorf(\"argument %q contains path traversal\", arg)\n538:         }\n539:     }\n540:     \n541:     // 4. Validate environment variables\n542:     for _, env := range cmd.Env {\n543:         if strings.HasPrefix(env, \"LD_PRELOAD\") || strings.HasPrefix(env, \"LD_LIBRARY_PATH\") {\n544:             return fmt.Errorf(\"dangerous environment variable: %s\", env)\n545:         }\n546:     }\n547:     \n548:     return nil\n549: }\n550: \n551: func IsPathSafe(path, workDir string) bool {\n552:     absPath, err := filepath.Abs(path)\n553:     if err != nil {\n554:         return false\n555:     }\n556:     \n557:     absWorkDir, err := filepath.Abs(workDir)\n558:     if err != nil {\n559:         return false\n560:     }\n561:     \n562:     return strings.HasPrefix(absPath, absWorkDir)\n563: }\n564: ```\n565: \n566: ## Configuration\n567: \n568: ### Environment Variables\n569: \n570: | Variable | Required | Default | Notes |\n571: |----------|----------|---------|-------|\n572: | `PICOD_WORKDIR` | No | `/tmp/picod` | Base working directory |\n573: | `PICOD_DEFAULT_TIMEOUT` | No | `30s` | Default command timeout |\n574: | `PICOD_MAX_MEMORY` | No | `128Mi` | Default memory limit |\n575: | `PICOD_MAX_CPU` | No | `1.0` | Default CPU limit |\n576: | `PICOD_MAX_OUTPUT_SIZE` | No | `10MB` | Default output size limit |\n577: | `PICOD_MAX_PROCESSES` | No | `10` | Default process limit |\n578: \n579: ### Example Configuration\n580: \n581: ```go\n582: config := &Config{\n583:     WorkDir:        \"/tmp/picod\",\n584:     DefaultTimeout: 30 * time.Second,\n585:     MaxMemory:      128 * 1024 * 1024, // 128 MiB\n586:     MaxCPU:         1.0,\n587:     MaxOutputSize:  10 * 1024 * 1024, // 10 MiB\n588:     MaxProcesses:   10,\n589: }\n590: ```\n591: \n592: ## Testing Strategy\n593: \n594: ### Unit Tests\n595: \n596: | Test | Purpose |\n597: |------|---------|\n598: | `TestPicoD_Run_Success` | Basic command execution |\n599: | `TestPicoD_Run_Timeout` | Command exceeds timeout |\n600: | `TestPicoD_Run_OOM` | Command exceeds memory limit |\n601: | `TestPicoD_Run_Cancelled` | Context cancellation |\n602: | `TestPicoD_OutputCapture` | Stdout/stderr capture |\n603: | `TestPicoD_SecurityValidation` | Invalid commands rejected |\n604: | `TestPicoD_ResourceLimits_Validate` | Resource limit validation |\n605: | `TestPicoD_SecurityOpts_Validate` | Security options validation |\n606: | `TestPicoD_WithOptions` | Functional options pattern |\n607: | `TestPicoD_ExecutionErrorTypes` | Error type classification |\n608: \n609: ### Integration Tests\n610: \n611: | Test | Purpose |\n612: |------|---------|\n613: | `TestPicoD_Integration_FullLifecycle` | Full execution flow |\n614: | `TestPicoD_Integration_Concurrent` | Multiple concurrent commands |\n615: | `TestPicoD_Integration_ResourceLimits` | Verify limits are enforced |\n616: | `TestPicoD_Integration_Streaming` | Output streaming functionality |\n617: | `TestPicoD_Integration_SignalHandling` | Process signal handling |\n618: \n619: ### Test Fixtures\n620: \n621: ```go\n622: // mockOutputHandler implements OutputHandler for testing\n623: type mockOutputHandler struct {\n624:     stdoutCalls [][]byte\n625:     stderrCalls [][]byte\n626:     completeCalled bool\n627:     lastResult *CommandResult\n628: }\n629: \n630: func (m *mockOutputHandler) OnStdout(data []byte) {\n631:     m.stdoutCalls = append(m.stdoutCalls, data)\n632: }\n633: \n634: func (m *mockOutputHandler) OnStderr(data []byte) {\n635:     m.stderrCalls = append(m.stderrCalls, data)\n636: }\n637: \n638: func (m *mockOutputHandler) OnComplete(result *CommandResult) {\n639:     m.completeCalled = true\n640:     m.lastResult = result\n641: }\n642: ```\n643: \n644: ## Acceptance Criteria\n645: \n646: - [ ] `PicoD` struct implements all required methods\n647: - [ ] Resource limits are enforced (timeout, CPU, memory, output size)\n648: - [ ] Output capture works correctly (stdout, stderr, exit code)\n649: - [ ] Cancellation via context is supported\n650: - [ ] Security validations prevent dangerous operations\n651: - [ ] Streaming output is supported\n652: - [ ] All unit tests pass\n653: - [ ] Integration tests pass\n654: - [ ] Code coverage >= 80%\n655: - [ ] Documentation includes usage examples\n656: - [ ] Error types are properly classified and documented\n657: \n658: ## Dependencies\n659: \n660: | Package | Purpose |\n661: |---------|---------|\n662: | `context` | Command cancellation and timeouts |\n663: | `os/exec` | Command execution primitives |\n664: | `syscall` | Process management and signals |\n665: | `k8s.io/klog/v2` | Structured logging |\n666: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/common/types` | SandboxInfo type definitions |\n667: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1` | Type definitions |\n668: \n669: ## Affected Components\n670: \n671: 1. **Sandbox Manager** (`pkg/workloadmanager/sandbox/`): Will use PicoD for command execution within sandboxes\n672: 2. **Workload Manager** (`pkg/workloadmanager/`): Will invoke PicoD APIs for job execution\n673: 3. **Code Interpreter** (standalone daemon): Will use PicoD execution logic\n674: 4. **Security Module**: Will configure security policies for command execution\n675: 5. **Monitoring System**: Will collect metrics from command execution\n676: \n677: ## References\n678: \n679: - AR-012: Sandbox Infrastructure\n680: - AR-013: Session Storage\n681: - AR-014: Valkey Storage\n682: - `code-execution/spec.md`: PicoD Specification\n683: - `code-execution/design.md`: PicoD Design\n684: - `deployment/client-go.md`: Kubernetes Client-Go\n\n(End of file - total 684 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Design: AR-015 PicoD Command Execution API\n\n## Overview\n\n| Item | Value |\n|------|-------|\n| AR | AR-015 — PicoD Command Execution API |\n| Module | `pkg/picod` |\n| Language | Go |\n| Size | M |\n| Stage | ST-1 completed |\n\nThis document describes the technical implementation for the PicoD command execution API within `pkg/picod`. The PicoD module provides secure, resource-limited command execution capabilities for the AgentCube platform, serving as the execution engine for code interpreters and agent runtimes.\n\n## Architecture\n\n### Component Structure\n\n```\npkg/picod/","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/pkg/picod/design.md","time":{"start":1775861326426,"end":1775861326448}}}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1775861326478,"sessionID":"ses_2866ae9a5ffeJaOf2Df4gOXgas","part":{"id":"prt_d79956273001gB1hcpHekw3SiK","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","messageID":"msg_d79954c40001paCR5nN5B4du3f","sessionID":"ses_2866ae9a5ffeJaOf2Df4gOXgas","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":22974,"input":6,"output":182,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":3535,"read":19251}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775861329147,"sessionID":"ses_2866ae9a5ffeJaOf2Df4gOXgas","part":{"id":"prt_d79956cfa001xmvUmlN1frVJ48","messageID":"msg_d799562a5001uIpZppv5A3Vj9q","sessionID":"ses_2866ae9a5ffeJaOf2Df4gOXgas","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1775861330898,"sessionID":"ses_2866ae9a5ffeJaOf2Df4gOXgas","part":{"id":"prt_d79956e9e001sPCh2fsgvVyNcI","messageID":"msg_d799562a5001uIpZppv5A3Vj9q","sessionID":"ses_2866ae9a5ffeJaOf2Df4gOXgas","type":"text","text":"Now I understand the context. I need to write a `proposal.md` for **AR-017: PicoD JWT Middleware** in the `pkg/picod` module. This follows the pattern of AR-015 and will add JWT authentication middleware to the PicoD HTTP daemon. Let me create the proposal:","time":{"start":1775861330896,"end":1775861330896}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775861402486,"sessionID":"ses_2866ae9a5ffeJaOf2Df4gOXgas","part":{"id":"prt_d799573d30012eqOJP45ALgPYz","messageID":"msg_d799562a5001uIpZppv5A3Vj9q","sessionID":"ses_2866ae9a5ffeJaOf2Df4gOXgas","type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"toolu_fd387697d7de49bf8a082a5c","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-017-proposal.md","content":"# AR-017: PicoD JWT Middleware\n\n## Purpose\n\nThis proposal implements JWT (JSON Web Token) authentication middleware for the PicoD HTTP daemon in the `pkg/picod` module. The goal is to:\n\n1. **Secure API Access** - Protect PicoD HTTP endpoints with RSA-based JWT authentication\n2. **Token Validation** - Validate JWT tokens signed with RSA private keys using the corresponding public key\n3. **Request Authorization** - Intercept and authenticate incoming HTTP requests before allowing access to command execution APIs\n4. **Flexible Configuration** - Support configuration via environment variables and command-line flags\n5. **Health Endpoint Protection** - Optionally protect the health check endpoint with JWT authentication\n\nThis implementation builds upon the PicoD execution infrastructure established in AR-015 and provides the security layer required for multi-tenant code interpreter deployments.\n\n## Scope\n\n**Module:** `pkg/picod`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** S\n\nThis AR covers:\n\n- **In scope:**\n  - JWT middleware implementation (`middleware.go`)\n  - JWT token validation logic (`jwt.go`)\n  - RSA key handling utilities (`crypto.go`)\n  - Configuration via environment variables and flags\n  - Unit tests with mocked tokens and keys\n  - Integration tests with real HTTP server\n  - Error handling and logging\n\n- **Out of scope:**\n  - JWT token generation (handled by external auth service)\n  - Token refresh mechanisms\n  - User/role-based authorization (only authentication)\n  - OAuth2 or other authentication protocols\n  - Session management (covered in AR-013)\n  - PicoD HTTP server implementation (covered in `code-execution/` specs)\n\n## Current State Analysis\n\n### Existing PicoD Infrastructure\n\nThe current PicoD system has command execution infrastructure:\n\n1. **PicoD Core** (`pkg/picod/picod.go`):\n   - Main `PicoD` struct with sandbox ID, work directory, limits, and security options\n   - Functional options pattern for configuration\n   - Structured logging with klog\n\n2. **Command Execution** (`pkg/picod/executor.go`):\n   - `Run()` and `Start()` methods for command execution\n   - Resource limit enforcement (timeout, CPU, memory, output size)\n   - Output capture and streaming\n\n3. **Security Module** (`pkg/picod/security.go`):\n   - Command validation and path safety checks\n   - Privilege dropping and capability management\n   - Allowlist-based command selection\n\n4. **Configuration** (`pkg/picod/config.go`):\n   - Environment variable loading\n   - Default values for resource limits\n\n### Gaps Identified\n\n1. **No HTTP authentication** - PicoD HTTP daemon has no authentication layer\n2. **No JWT validation** - Cannot validate JWT tokens from incoming requests\n3. **No RSA key handling** - Missing utilities for loading and using RSA public keys\n4. **No middleware pattern** - No HTTP middleware for request interception\n5. **Health endpoint exposed** - Health check endpoint is publicly accessible\n\n### PicoD HTTP Context\n\nPer `code-execution/design.md` and `code-execution/spec.md`:\n- PicoD is an HTTP daemon that runs commands inside a configurable workspace jail\n- Exposes health endpoint with JWT (RSA)-protected APIs\n- CLI flags: `-port` (default 8080), `-workspace` (default: current working directory)\n- Server uses `ReadHeaderTimeout` of 10 seconds\n- Authentication modes: `picod` (JWT required) or `none` (no auth)\n\n### Kubernetes Client-Go Context\n\nPer `deployment/client-go.md`:\n- Generated Kubernetes client for `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1`\n- `CodeInterpreter` CRD supports `AuthMode` enum (`picod` or `none`)\n- Workload manager injects `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` when `AuthMode=picod`\n- Public key provided as base64-encoded PEM string\n\n## Proposed Changes\n\n### 1. JWT Middleware (`middleware.go`)\n\n```go\n// JWTMiddleware is HTTP middleware that validates JWT tokens\ntype JWTMiddleware struct {\n    // publicKey is the RSA public key for token validation\n    publicKey *rsa.PublicKey\n    \n    // skipPaths is a list of paths to skip authentication\n    skipPaths map[string]bool\n    \n    // logger is the structured logger\n    logger klog.Logger\n}\n\n// NewJWTMiddleware creates a new JWT middleware\nfunc NewJWTMiddleware(publicKey *rsa.PublicKey, skipPaths ...string) *JWTMiddleware\n\n// Middleware returns the HTTP middleware handler\nfunc (m *JWTMiddleware) Middleware(next http.Handler) http.Handler\n\n// extractToken extracts the JWT token from the Authorization header\nfunc (m *JWTMiddleware) extractToken(r *http.Request) (string, error)\n\n// shouldSkip checks if a path should skip authentication\nfunc (m *JWTMiddleware) shouldSkip(path string) bool\n```\n\n### 2. JWT Validation (`jwt.go`)\n\n```go\n// Claims represents JWT token claims\ntype Claims struct {\n    // Subject is the token subject\n    Sub string `json:\"sub\"`\n    \n    // Issuer is the token issuer\n    Iss string `json:\"iss\"`\n    \n    // Audience is the token audience\n    Aud string `json:\"aud\"`\n    \n    // Expiration time\n    Exp int64 `json:\"exp\"`\n    \n    // Issued at\n    Iat int64 `json:\"iat\"`\n    \n    // Custom claims for AgentCube\n    SandboxID string `json:\"sandbox_id,omitempty\"`\n    Namespace string `json:\"namespace,omitempty\"`\n}\n\n// Validate validates the JWT claims\nfunc (c *Claims) Validate(now time.Time) error\n\n// ParseAndValidate parses and validates a JWT token\nfunc ParseAndValidate(tokenString string, publicKey *rsa.PublicKey) (*Claims, error)\n\n// VerifySignature verifies the JWT signature\nfunc VerifySignature(tokenString string, publicKey *rsa.PublicKey) error\n```\n\n### 3. RSA Key Handling (`crypto.go`)\n\n```go\n// LoadPublicKey loads an RSA public key from PEM-encoded data\nfunc LoadPublicKey(pemData []byte) (*rsa.PublicKey, error)\n\n// LoadPublicKeyFromBase64 loads an RSA public key from base64-encoded PEM\nfunc LoadPublicKeyFromBase64(base64PEM string) (*rsa.PublicKey, error)\n\n// ParsePEM parses PEM-encoded data and returns the RSA public key\nfunc ParsePEM(pemBlock *pem.Block) (*rsa.PublicKey, error)\n\n// GenerateKeyPair generates an RSA key pair for testing\nfunc GenerateKeyPair(bits int) (*rsa.PrivateKey, *rsa.PublicKey, error)\n```\n\n### 4. Configuration\n\n#### Environment Variables\n\n| Variable | Required | Default | Notes |\n|----------|----------|---------|-------|\n| `PICOD_AUTH_PUBLIC_KEY` | Conditional | `` | Base64-encoded PEM RSA public key (required if `-auth=picod`) |\n| `PICOD_AUTH_MODE` | No | `none` | Authentication mode (`picod` or `none`) |\n| `PICOD_AUTH_SKIP_PATHS` | No | `/health` | Comma-separated list of paths to skip auth |\n\n#### Command-Line Flags\n\n```go\n// Add to existing PicoD flag parsing\nflag.StringVar(&authMode, \"auth\", \"none\", \"Authentication mode: picod or none\")\nflag.StringVar(&publicKeyPEM, \"public-key\", \"\", \"RSA public key (base64-encoded PEM)\")\nflag.StringVar(&skipPaths, \"skip-paths\", \"/health\", \"Comma-separated paths to skip auth\")\n```\n\n### 5. Error Handling\n\n```go\n// AuthError represents an authentication error\ntype AuthError struct {\n    // Type is the error type\n    Type AuthErrorType\n    \n    // Message is the error message\n    Message string\n    \n    // Underlying is the underlying error\n    Underlying error\n}\n\ntype AuthErrorType string\n\nconst (\n    AuthErrorMissingToken  AuthErrorType = \"missing_token\"\n    AuthErrorInvalidToken  AuthErrorType = \"invalid_token\"\n    AuthErrorExpiredToken  AuthErrorType = \"expired_token\"\n    AuthErrorInvalidSig    AuthErrorType = \"invalid_signature\"\n    AuthErrorInvalidClaims AuthErrorType = \"invalid_claims\"\n    AuthErrorInternal      AuthErrorType = \"internal_error\"\n)\n\n// HTTPResponse returns the appropriate HTTP status code\nfunc (e *AuthError) HTTPStatus() int\n```\n\n### 6. HTTP Response Helpers\n\n```go\n// WriteJSON writes a JSON response\nfunc WriteJSON(w http.ResponseWriter, status int, data interface{})\n\n// WriteError writes an error response\nfunc WriteError(w http.ResponseWriter, err error)\n\n// HealthResponse represents a health check response\ntype HealthResponse struct {\n    // Status is the health status\n    Status string `json:\"status\"`\n    \n    // Timestamp is the current time\n    Timestamp time.Time `json:\"timestamp\"`\n    \n    // SandboxID is the sandbox identifier\n    SandboxID string `json:\"sandbox_id,omitempty\"`\n}\n```\n\n### 7. Integration with Existing Code\n\n```go\n// SetupHTTPServer creates the HTTP server with JWT middleware\nfunc SetupHTTPServer(picod *PicoD, config *Config) (*http.Server, error) {\n    mux := http.NewServeMux()\n    \n    // Health endpoint (optionally protected)\n    mux.HandleFunc(\"/health\", handleHealth(picod))\n    \n    // Command execution endpoints (protected)\n    mux.HandleFunc(\"/api/v1/execute\", handleExecute(picod))\n    mux.HandleFunc(\"/api/v1/execute/stream\", handleExecuteStream(picod))\n    \n    // Apply JWT middleware\n    var handler http.Handler = mux\n    if config.AuthMode == \"picod\" {\n        publicKey, err := LoadPublicKeyFromBase64(config.PublicKeyPEM)\n        if err != nil {\n            return nil, fmt.Errorf(\"failed to load public key: %w\", err)\n        }\n        \n        middleware := NewJWTMiddleware(publicKey, config.SkipPaths...)\n        handler = middleware.Middleware(mux)\n    }\n    \n    return &http.Server{\n        Addr:              fmt.Sprintf(\":%d\", config.Port),\n        Handler:           handler,\n        ReadHeaderTimeout: 10 * time.Second,\n    }, nil\n}\n```\n\n## Impact Analysis\n\n### Dependencies\n\n| Package | Purpose |\n|---------|---------|\n| `crypto/rsa` | RSA signature verification |\n| `crypto/x509` | X.509 key parsing |\n| `encoding/pem` | PEM decoding |\n| `encoding/base64` | Base64 decoding |\n| `encoding/json` | JSON encoding/decoding |\n| `net/http` | HTTP middleware |\n| `strings` | String manipulation |\n| `time` | Time-based token validation |\n| `k8s.io/klog/v2` | Structured logging |\n\n### Affected Components\n\n1. **PicoD HTTP Server** (`code-execution/`): Will integrate JWT middleware into HTTP server setup\n2. **Workload Manager** (`pkg/workloadmanager/`): Will configure auth mode and inject public key\n3. **Code Interpreter Controller** (`pkg/controller/`): Will set `AuthMode` on `CodeInterpreter` spec\n4. **Authentication Service** (external): Will generate JWT tokens for clients\n5. **Client Applications**: Will include JWT tokens in `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header\n\n### Backward Compatibility\n\n- Default auth mode is `none` (no authentication) for backward compatibility\n- Existing deployments without `AuthMode=picod` continue to work unchanged\n- Public key injection is optional and only required when `AuthMode=picod`\n- Health endpoint can be configured to skip authentication\n\n### Risk Assessment\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|------|------------|--------|------------|\n| Token forgery | Low | Critical | Use RSA-256/512 signatures, verify with strong crypto |\n| Key leakage | Low | Critical | Keys managed by Kubernetes secrets, not in code |\n| Token replay | Medium | High | Include `iat` and `exp` claims, use short-lived tokens |\n| Clock skew | Medium | Medium | Allow configurable clock skew tolerance (30s) |\n| Performance overhead | Low | Low | RSA verification is fast (<1ms per request) |\n| DoS via invalid tokens | Medium | Low | Rate limiting, early rejection of malformed tokens |\n\n## Alternatives Considered\n\n### Alternative 1: Use Existing JWT Library (e.g., golang-jwt/jwt)\n\n**Approach**: Leverage the popular `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` library\n\n**Pros**:\n- Battle-tested, widely used\n- Handles edge cases (clock skew, token parsing)\n- Active community support\n- Supports multiple signature algorithms\n\n**Cons**:\n- Additional dependency\n- May be overkill for simple RSA verification\n- Larger binary size\n\n**Decision**: Use a minimal custom implementation for simplicity and control, but structure code to easily swap in `golang-jwt/jwt` if needed. The custom implementation will follow JWT standards (RFC 7519) for compatibility.\n\n### Alternative 2: Kubernetes ServiceAccount Token\n\n**Approach**: Use Kubernetes native ServiceAccount tokens for authentication\n\n**Pros**:\n- Native Kubernetes integration\n- No additional key management\n- Automatic token rotation\n\n**Cons**:\n- Requires Kubernetes API access for validation\n- Tightly couples PicoD to Kubernetes\n- More complex validation logic\n- Not suitable for non-Kubernetes deployments\n\n**Decision**: Use RSA-based JWT for deployment flexibility and simpler validation. PicoD should work both inside and outside Kubernetes.\n\n### Alternative 3: mTLS (Mutual TLS)\n\n**Approach**: Use mutual TLS for client authentication\n\n**Pros**:\n- Strong security (certificate-based)\n- Built into Go's `http.Server`\n- No custom token handling\n\n**Cons**:\n- Complex certificate management\n- Requires CA infrastructure\n- Harder to debug\n- Less flexible for distributed systems\n\n**Decision**: Use JWT for simpler token-based authentication. mTLS is better suited for service-to-service communication at the infrastructure level.\n\n### Alternative 4: API Key Authentication\n\n**Approach**: Use simple API keys in headers\n\n**Pros**:\n- Simple implementation\n- Easy to debug\n- Low overhead\n\n**Cons**:\n- No standard claims structure\n- Harder to distribute and rotate\n- No built-in expiration\n- Less secure (symmetric keys)\n\n**Decision**: Use JWT with RSA signatures for better security, standard claims, and asymmetric key distribution.\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Unit Tests\n\n1. **TestJWTMiddleware_ValidToken**: Valid JWT token passes through\n2. **TestJWTMiddleware_MissingToken**: Missing token returns 401\n3. **TestJWTMiddleware_InvalidToken**: Malformed token returns 401\n4. **TestJWTMiddleware_ExpiredToken**: Expired token returns 401\n5. **TestJWTMiddleware_SkipPath**: Health endpoint skips auth\n6. **TestParseAndValidate_Success**: Valid token parses claims correctly\n7. **TestParseAndValidate_InvalidSignature**: Tampered token fails verification\n8. **TestClaims_Validate_Expired**: Expired claims fail validation\n9. **TestClaims_Validate_Future**: Not-yet-valid claims fail validation\n10. **TestLoadPublicKeyFromBase64**: Correctly loads base64-encoded PEM key\n11. **TestLoadPublicKey_InvalidPEM**: Invalid PEM returns error\n12. **TestAuthError_HTTPStatus**: Error types map to correct HTTP codes\n\n### Integration Tests\n\n1. **TestJWTMiddleware_Integration_FullFlow**: Full HTTP request with valid token\n2. **TestJWTMiddleware_Integration_MultipleRequests**: Multiple concurrent requests\n3. **TestJWTMiddleware_Integration_KeyRotation**: Server handles key change (restart)\n4. **TestJWTMiddleware_Integration_HealthEndpoint**: Health endpoint with/without auth\n\n### Test Fixtures\n\n```go\n// generateTestToken creates a signed JWT token for testing\nfunc generateTestToken(privateKey *rsa.PrivateKey, claims *Claims) (string, error)\n\n// testClaims returns standard test claims\nfunc testClaims() *Claims {\n    return &Claims{\n        Sub:       \"test-user\",\n        Iss:       \"test-issuer\",\n        Aud:       \"picod\",\n        Exp:       time.Now().Add(1 * time.Hour).Unix(),\n        Iat:       time.Now().Unix(),\n        SandboxID: \"test-sandbox\",\n        Namespace: \"default\",\n    }\n}\n\n// generateTestKeyPair creates a test RSA key pair\nfunc generateTestKeyPair() (*rsa.PrivateKey, *rsa.PublicKey, error)\n```\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] JWT middleware correctly validates tokens\n- [ ] Invalid/missing tokens return 401 Unauthorized\n- [ ] Expired tokens are rejected\n- [ ] Signature verification works with RSA public key\n- [ ] Configurable skip paths work correctly\n- [ ] Health endpoint can be protected or public\n- [ ] Claims are correctly parsed and validated\n- [ ] Error types map to appropriate HTTP status codes\n- [ ] All unit tests pass\n- [ ] Integration tests pass\n- [ ] Code coverage >= 80%\n- [ ] Documentation includes usage examples\n- [ ] Compatible with standard JWT libraries (e.g., PyJWT, jose)\n\n## References\n\n- AR-015: PicoD Command Execution API\n- AR-013: Session Storage\n- `code-execution/spec.md`: PicoD Specification\n- `code-execution/design.md`: PicoD Design\n- `deployment/client-go.md`: Kubernetes Client-Go\n- `deployment/spec.md`: Deployment Configuration\n- RFC 7519: JSON Web Token (JWT)\n- RFC 7515: JSON Web Signature (JWS)\n"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-017-proposal.md","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/AR-017-proposal.md","time":{"start":1775861402472,"end":1775861402483}}}}
